Data validation¶

This data set has 947 rows, 8 columns including the recipe identifier. I have validated all variables and I have not made any changes after validation. All the columns are just as described in the data dictionary:

  • recipe: 947 unique identifiers without missing values, same as the description. No cleaning is needed.
  • calories: 52 missing values, the variable has a right skewed distribution so I used the median to impute the missing values.
  • carbohydrate: 52 missing values, the variable has a right skewed distribution so I used the median to impute the missing values.
  • sugar: 52 missing values, the variable has a right skewed distribution so I used the median to impute the missing values.
  • protein: 52 missing values, the variable has a right skewed distribution so I used the median to impute the missing values.
  • category: No missing values, I have replaced value 'Chicken Breast' with the correct string and I have converted the column dtype to categorical nominal.
  • servings: No missing values, I have replaced values ['4 as a snack', '6 as a snack'] with the correct string and I have converted the column dtype to integer.
  • high_traffic: Same as description. The target is binary so I have replaced 'High' value with 1 and null values with 0.

Model Fitting & Evaluation¶

Predicting which recipes will be popular is a classification problem in machine learning. It is a binary classification problem since the target variable has only 2 possible outputs.

I am choosing the Gaussian Naive Bayes Classifier because it is a simple model that assumes feature independence between classes, that is null correlation between the features and the target, it also does not require the data to be standardized, is efficient to train and generally produces good results. The comparision model I am choosing is the Random Forest Classifier because tree models can capture non-linear relationships between explanatory variables and the target variable very accurately, also ensemble methods are more robust to overfitting.

For the evaluation, I am choosing Precision and Recall to evaluate the model. Recall minimizes the number of False Negatives that is equivalent to increase the number of True Positives (absolute number of high traffic recipes predicted correctly) while precision minimizes the number of False Positives, we want a Precision>=0.8 since we want high traffic predicted recipes to be correct 80% of the time.

Prepare Data for Modelling¶

To enable modelling, we chose calories,carbohydrate,sugar,protein,category,servings as features and high_traffic as target variable. I also have made the following changes:

  • Replace outliers in numerical columns with the median and apply a log transformation.
  • Convert the categorical variables into numeric features
  • Split the data into a training set and a test set, using stratified method.

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

First I define a function that returns the lowerbound and upperbound of a numeric column. Then I apply it to the numeric columns:

In [88]:
def outlier_detector(datacolumn):
    Q1,Q3 = np.percentile(datacolumn,[25,75])
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1-(1.5*IQR)
    upper_bound = Q3+(1.5*IQR)
    return lower_bound,upper_bound
In [89]:
numeric=['calories','carbohydrate','sugar','protein']
for i in numeric:
    lowerbound, upperbound = outlier_detector(df[i])
    median = df[i].median()
    df.loc[((df[i] > upperbound)|(df[i] < lowerbound)), i] = median

Finding the best parameter for Random Forest Classifier Model¶

In [98]:
train_score = []
test_score = []
max_score = 0
max_pair = (0,0)

for i in range(1,50):
    rf = RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=i,random_state=7)
    rf.fit(X_train,y_train)
    y_pred_test = rf.predict(X_test)
    y_pred_train = rf.predict(X_train)
    train_score.append(precision_score(y_train,y_pred_train))
    test_score.append(precision_score(y_test,y_pred_test))
    test_pair = (i,precision_score(y_test,y_pred_test))
    if test_pair[1] > max_pair[1]:
        max_pair = test_pair
        best_rf = rf

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(np.arange(1,50), train_score, label = "Training precision",color='lightcoral')
ax.plot(np.arange(1,50), test_score, label = "Testing precision",color='lime')
print(f'Best max_depth is: {max_pair[0]} \nTesting precision is: {max_pair[1]}')

Best max_depth is: 8 
Testing precision is: 0.8208092485549133

Results¶

The Recall of the Gaussian Naive Bayes, and the Random Forest Classifier model is 0.57 and 0.82, meaning the Random Forest Classifier model predicts a higher absolute number of high traffic recipes which are actually high traffic recipes. The Precision of the Gaussian Naive Bayes, and the Random Forest Classifier model is 0.9 and 0.82, meaning the Gaussian Naive Bayes predicts a higher percentage of correctly predicted high traffic recipes .

Evaluate by Business Criteria¶

The company wants to predict which recipes will lead to high traffic and also ensure that the predictions are correct 80% of the time. Therefore, we would consider using Recall and Pecision as KPIs, precision of predictions should be higher than 80% all the time to ensure that at least 80% of high traffic recipes predicted are correct while we should monitor recall to check the ability of the model to discriminate a high percentage of high traffic recipes.

Both models reach the 80% Precision threshold, Gaussian Naive Bayes has a precision of 90% while the random forest classifier reaches 82%. Random Forest Classifier achieves a Recall of 82% while Gaussian Naive Bayes only reaches 57% so random forest performs much better on that metric.

Recommendation¶

To ensure that only high traffic recipes are displayed on the homepage each day we can plan to deploy this Random Forest Classifier into production. By implementing this model, above 80% of the high traffic recipes predicted will generate high traffic on the website. This will increase the subscriptions and generate more revenue. I will recommend the following steps to ensure the model can be deployed and improved regularly.

  1. Test the model in the recent month and compare the traffic on the website with respect to the previous month.
  2. Identify and fix errors to improve recall and precision after testing.
  3. Fully deploy the model using an efficient deployment strategy, such as a web or mobile application or API.
  4. Continuously improve the model by collecting more data, feature engineer and fine tuning parameter. This would be the key points to maintain a high precision in the predictions over time while continuing achieving a high recall.
